    {
      "citation_id": "[CITATION_10]",
      "span_text": "A number of placebo-controlled clinical trials have shown that fesoterodine, imidafenacin, propiverine, solifenacin, and tolterodine were statistically significantly more effective at reducing the mean number of urgency episodes/24 h compared with placebo ( Figure 6 ). Pooled differences in mean changes from baseline varied between 0.4 and 1.7 episodes per day compared with placebo."
    },
    {
      "citation_id": "[CITATION_11]",
      "span_text": "Trospium chloride extended release was also statistically significantly more effective at reducing the mean number of severe urgency episodes/24 h (IUSS) compared with placebo."
    },
    {
      "citation_id": "[CITATION_12]",
      "span_text": "There was some evidence favoring daily doses of solifenacin 5 mg and 10 mg compared with tolterodine 4 mg, and solifenacin 10 mg compared with propiverine 20 mg."
    },
    {
      "citation_id": "[CITATION_13]",
      "span_text": "Trospium chloride extended release was also statistically significantly more effective at reducing the mean number of severe urgency episodes/24 h (IUSS) compared with placebo. There was some evidence favoring daily doses of solifenacin 5 mg and 10 mg compared with tolterodine 4 mg, and solifenacin 10 mg compared with propiverine 20 mg. Treatment with antimuscarinic agents also significantly reduces the incidence of severe urgency in subjects with OAB and increases the warning time to the onset of an urgency episode compared with placebo. Clinically meaningful improvement in symptoms of urgency and severe urgency may begin within the first few days of antimuscarinic treatment. Dose escalation of antimuscarinic agents may further improve urgency symptoms compared with lower doses of the same agent; however, the antimuscarinic burden is more likely to increase (dry mouth, constipation, etc.) resulting in a decreased rate of persistence. This is an important consideration, especially when treating elderly OAB patients."
    },
    {
      "citation_id": "[CITATION_14]",
      "span_text": "Trospium chloride extended release was also statistically significantly more effective at reducing the mean number of severe urgency episodes/24 h (IUSS) compared with placebo. There was some evidence favoring daily doses of solifenacin 5 mg and 10 mg compared with tolterodine 4 mg, and solifenacin 10 mg compared with propiverine 20 mg. Treatment with antimuscarinic agents also significantly reduces the incidence of severe urgency in subjects with OAB and increases the warning time to the onset of an urgency episode compared with placebo. Clinically meaningful improvement in symptoms of urgency and severe urgency may begin within the first few days of antimuscarinic treatment. Dose escalation of antimuscarinic agents may further improve urgency symptoms compared with lower doses of the same agent; however, the antimuscarinic burden is more likely to increase (dry mouth, constipation, etc.) resulting in a decreased rate of persistence. This is an important consideration, especially when treating elderly OAB patients."
    },
